  "text": "In the model that does not account for educational composition, the Singapore population (made up of Singapore citizens and permanent residents) was divided into three groups as seen in Fig 1: the population under 60, active (functionally able) elderly, and functionally disabled elderly. Within each group, the population was further sub-divided by age (single age cohorts from age 0-age 59 years for the under 60 group and single age cohorts from age 60-age 100 and older for the active and functionally disabled elderly groups) and gender. The population under 60 increases via births and immigration and decreases via deaths, emigration and becoming elderly (aging from 59 to 60). Births were calculated based on the female reproductive age cohort (aged and their corresponding fertility rates [62] while deaths were calculated using mortality rates for each age cohort obtained from life tables [62] . Emigration was estimated by calibration [CITATION_1] . The aging process ensures that at the end of every year, the surviving population in each age cohort transitions to the subsequent cohort except for the final age cohort (aged 100 and older). The model configuration allows elderly Singaporeans to transition between the active and functional disability states, or flow out from either state as they die or emigrate. Disability transition probability estimates used here were not specific for education.",
